From c375de9a7b35ae65dbe90f152cc4be724d4bfa91 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Dong Chenchen <superdcc97@163.com>
Date: Wed, 8 Apr 2026 16:58:16 +0800
Subject: [PATCH 06/27] sched: add read/write_lock_tasklist_all() helpers (no
 callers yet)

Introduce four static inline helpers that take or release every
NUMA-domain shard's lock plus the inner tasklist_lock, in the
established acquisition order (shards 0..N-1, then tasklist_lock,
release in reverse).

These are intended for the cold-path callers that genuinely need a
globally consistent snapshot of the entire process list -- oom kill
scan, sysrq-t, kdb backtrace, full /proc walk, coredump enumeration,
etc.  By going through the per-shard locks they will, once migrated,
serialise correctly against the per-fork shard locking introduced in
the previous commit, instead of relying on the global tasklist_lock
alone.

This commit only adds the API.  No caller is migrated; existing
cold-path callers continue to use plain read_lock(&tasklist_lock) /
write_lock(&tasklist_lock).  The migration is intentionally split
out so each converted caller can be reviewed and lockdep-validated
on its own; in particular, lockdep nesting annotations will need to
be added for any caller that takes the shard locks in a loop, since
nr_node_ids may exceed MAX_LOCKDEP_SUBCLASSES on big NUMA boxes.

Because there are no callers in this commit, the helpers are not
instantiated and the change is a pure header-only API addition with
zero behavioural impact.

Signed-off-by: Dong Chenchen <superdcc97@163.com>
---
 include/linux/sched/task.h | 71 ++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
 1 file changed, 71 insertions(+)

diff --git a/include/linux/sched/task.h b/include/linux/sched/task.h
index 6e5178549d08..6f3912f4911e 100644
--- a/include/linux/sched/task.h
+++ b/include/linux/sched/task.h
@@ -126,6 +126,77 @@ static inline void write_unlock_irq_task_domain(int nid)
 	write_unlock_irq(&task_domains[nid]->lock);
 }
 
+/*
+ * "Take every shard's lock plus tasklist_lock" helpers, for the cold-
+ * path callers that genuinely need a globally consistent snapshot of
+ * the entire process list (oom kill scan, sysrq-t, kdb backtrace,
+ * full /proc walk, coredump enumeration, ...).
+ *
+ * Acquisition order is fixed: shard 0, shard 1, ..., shard N-1, then
+ * tasklist_lock.  Release in reverse.  This matches the per-fork
+ * locking discipline (shard -> tasklist_lock -> siglock) used by
+ * copy_process()/release_task(), so the two never deadlock against
+ * each other.
+ *
+ * Phase 1 NOTE: introduced as a public API only.  No caller is
+ * migrated to use these in this commit -- existing cold-path
+ * callers continue to use plain read_lock(&tasklist_lock) /
+ * write_lock(&tasklist_lock), which still works because those
+ * callers do not need per-shard exclusion against fork/exit on
+ * other nodes.  A subsequent series will migrate the hot read-side
+ * cold paths (oom scan, signal broadcast, /proc walk) to these
+ * helpers, at which point lockdep nesting annotations will need to
+ * be added (see lockdep_set_class_and_subclass below).
+ *
+ * Lockdep nesting: nr_node_ids may exceed MAX_LOCKDEP_SUBCLASSES (8)
+ * on big NUMA boxes, so we cannot rely on _nested subclass numbering.
+ * For Phase 1 the helpers below are unused; when first migrated, the
+ * caller should either use lockdep_off()/lockdep_on() around the loop
+ * (acceptable for slow oom path) or arrange for each shard's lock to
+ * have a distinct lock class allocated at init_task_domains() time.
+ */
+static inline void read_lock_tasklist_all(void)
+{
+	int nid;
+
+	/*
+	 * init_task_domains() allocates a slot for every possible node,
+	 * so iterating [0, nr_node_ids) is safe whether the node is
+	 * online or not.  Acquire in ascending nid order, then the
+	 * inner tasklist_lock, matching copy_process()/release_task().
+	 */
+	for (nid = 0; nid < nr_node_ids; nid++)
+		read_lock(&task_domains[nid]->lock);
+	read_lock(&tasklist_lock);
+}
+
+static inline void read_unlock_tasklist_all(void)
+{
+	int nid;
+
+	read_unlock(&tasklist_lock);
+	for (nid = nr_node_ids - 1; nid >= 0; nid--)
+		read_unlock(&task_domains[nid]->lock);
+}
+
+static inline void write_lock_tasklist_all(void)
+{
+	int nid;
+
+	for (nid = 0; nid < nr_node_ids; nid++)
+		write_lock(&task_domains[nid]->lock);
+	write_lock(&tasklist_lock);
+}
+
+static inline void write_unlock_tasklist_all(void)
+{
+	int nid;
+
+	write_unlock(&tasklist_lock);
+	for (nid = nr_node_ids - 1; nid >= 0; nid--)
+		write_unlock(&task_domains[nid]->lock);
+}
+
 extern union thread_union init_thread_union;
 extern struct task_struct init_task;
 
